* Class 6 [2019-01-28 Mon]
** Mass Spectrometry
*** Determine chemical formula
*** Determine structural features
*** Workflow
**** HPLC separation
***** Stationary phase (solid)
***** Mobile phase (mix of liquid solvents)
***** Reverse phase is by far the most common separation technique
****** Stationary phase with C8 or C18 chains (nonpolar)
****** Mobile phase of polar molecules like methanol or acetonitrile
****** More polar molecules will elute faster
****** Solvents often get a proton source (usually an acid) to aid in ionization down the road
***** Issues:
****** You generally want your chromatography peak to be symmetrical
****** Your mobile phase is usually a mixture of solvents of variable polarity. The *gradient* of your solvents is what allows compounds in your sample to separate.
****** Sometimes an insufficient gradient results in asymmetric peaks
****** Sometimes your compounds all elute with the "solvent front"
***** 
**** Ionization
***** ESI/nanospray ESI
****** Compunds/solvents are run through a capillary tube with the same charge as the ionization mode
****** Charged solvent drops with compound ions are accelerated through an electromagnetic field
****** The droplets will eventually evaporate, expelling the compound ions, which are sent to the MS
**** Mass Analyzer
***** Cost anywhere between $500,000 and $1.5 million
***** Quadropole
****** Highly sensitive but relatively low mass resolution
****** Mass resolution = (ion mass)/(mass peak width)
****** Mass peak width = Accurate mass +/- (Accurate mass)/(Mass resolution)
****** Isobaric compounds are compounds with the same accurate mass but different structures
****** Mass resolution ~2000
***** TOF
****** Ions are provided in pulses
****** Mass resolution of ~40000
****** Time to reach detector is recorded
****** Maintains isotope distribution
****** The length of the chamber is used to determine time-of-flight, this can be thrown off by such slight things as differences in room temperature causing chamber to expand/shrink
****** Generally used for untargeted analyses
***** Orbitrap
****** Outer and central inner electrodes cause ions to orbit around central electrode
****** Mass resolution maximum 140000
****** However, you need to cut the resolution if you're combining with LC
****** Orbitraps mess with the natural isotope distribution you would expect to see
****** Also generally used for untargeted analyses
***** FT-ICR (Fourier Transform Icon Cyclotron Resonance)
****** Mass resolution 900000
****** Used for extremely difficult ions to tell apart
****** Can't perform liquid chromatography prior to running the sample (runs too slowly to handle LC waves)
**** Detection
