* Class 8 [2019-02-04 Mon]
** Peak Identification
*** What information can we glean?
**** m/z ratio
**** Retention time
**** Signal intensity
**** Fragmentation
**** Ion Mobility:
***** Ions separate based on:
****** Size
****** Shape
****** Charge
****** This provides orthogonal info that can distinguish stereoisomers
***** Traveling wave ionization (T-wave) is one way of doing this
****** Visualized with collisional cross section
*** Identification criteria (from the Metabolomics Society)
| Identifying Information                                                       | Score                        |
|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------+------------------------------|
| At least 2 independent orthogonal identifiers match an authentic identifiers  | 1 - identified               |
| e.g. precursor m/z and product m/z                                            |                              |
| e.g. precursor m/z and retention time                                         |                              |
| Physical chemical properties match literature and public/commercial libraries | 2 - putatively annotated     |
| Physiochemical properties match a known class                                 | 3 - putatively characterized |
| Precursor m/z observed                                                        | 4 - unknown                  |
* Class 9 [2019-02-11 Mon]
** GC/MS
*** Disadvantages
**** Need volatile compounds that can separate in a gaseous phase
**** 30-500 Da
**** Less common than LC/MS
*** GC is separating based off polarity and volatility
*** GC columns can be 30 meters or longer, giving it more resolving power
*** More [[https://teaching.shu.ac.uk/hwb/chemistry/tutorials/chrom/chrom1.htm][theoretical plates]]
*** The main advantage is resolving power
*** You can view fewer metabolites, but they separate much better than in LC
*** More consistent between instruments than LC too (more robust)
*** Tends to break down less, less expensive, easier to use
*** [[~/Documents/Notes/Images/GCvsLCvsNMR.png]]
** Volatile compounds
*** 11,164 different volatile compounds have been IDed in foods alone
*** Span all different types of chemical classes
*** Sample preparation is going to determine what type of compounds you're able to detect
*** No sample prep protocol captures all compounds in a sample
*** Basis of compound isolation
**** Solubility
***** Think about how sample prep affects quantitation. You might not be able to quantify polar compounds if you used a nonpolar solvent because you got a low proportion of the compound from the sample.
***** Aromatics you typically use an organic solvent
**** Volatility
*** Methods of isolating volatility
**** Direct sampling - just inject the sample straight into the machine
***** Won't be very concentrated
***** Need to have a high proportion of volatiles to get a signal
* Class 10 [2019-02-18 Mon]
** Gas Chromatography
*** GC is better at isolating compounds on the basis of volatility
*** Choosing solvents for extraction:
**** Solvents must be highly pure to avoid contaminants
*** Concentration of compounds in solvent (options):
**** Evaporate under a gentle stream of nitrogen - causes loss of volatiles
**** Vigreux fractional distillation - slower
**** Spinning band molecular distillation - expensive and slow but best distiller
*** Volatility:
**** Many factors influence partitioning of compounds into headspace (gas phase), such as solubility or temperature
**** Pass an inert gas through a food and trap volatile compounds
**** Dynamic vs static headspace methods
***** Dynamic is more selective but lower sensitivity
*** Instrumental setup:
**** On column or hot-port injection
**** Capillary columns:
***** Many phases: DB-Wax/DB-5
**** Carrier gas:
***** N2, He, H2
****** N2 and H2 are renewable
****** H2 is the best carrier but safety precautions are needed because its explosive
****** He is most popular at the moment but becoming prohibitively expensive
* Class 11 [2019-02-20 Wed]
** GC columns
*** Tightly wound coils of tube allow you to have much longer columns
*** Resolving power of GC column is defined by:
**** Length of column
**** Flow rate
**** Mixing of compounds
**** Diffusion 
**** Resistance of transfer to mobile phase
**** Viscosity constants
**** Look up what a Van Deemter plot means
**** Column diameter
*** Many times the resolution of the data is sacrificed in order to make the experiment more high throughput
*** The more viscous your carrier gas, the more time substances take to elute
** GC MS
*** Time-of-flight and Orbitrap are more common than quadrupole since they offer greater sensitivity, important in exploratory analysis
*** Ionization:
**** Electron Impact
**** Chemical Ionization
**** Low Energy EI
*** Fragmentation patterns tend to be a lot more consistent in GC since the ionization occurs in a background
** A feature is a data-derived object, a collection of M/Z peaks at a particular retention time
** A feature contains many fragments
** A metabolite can have many features
** Problems arise if you have too many or too few features
* Class 12 [2019-02-25 Mon]
** NMR
*** Quantitative
*** Reproducible
*** Expensive
*** Relatively low sensitivity
** NMR spectrum:
*** Chemical shift is expressed in ppm (hertz normalized for instrument)
*** Chemical shift is not immutable like mass; it depends on solvent, pH, concentration etc.
*** J coupling is the number of active neighboring nonequivalent nuclei (2nl + 1) or n + 1 for 1/2 spin nuclei
**** Number of mini peaks in the larger peak
*** Peak area is proportional to the number of nuclei contributing to the signal
**** Can be used for identification and quantification
*** Look up how to predict 1H NMR splitting patterns again
